<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   A Weighty Distinction
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<LP>
   Your July 12 page-one article concerning the world
standard of weight, "Le Gran K," failed to distinguish
between mass and weight. It was not clear whether Le Gran K
had lost 75-billionths of a kilogram of mass or 75-billionths
of a kilogram of weight in the past 100 years.
   The mass of an object is a measure of the amount of matter
in that object. The weight is the force due to the
gravitational attraction between the object and the Earth. If
Le Gran K is losing mass, then it is losing matter. In that
case, the cause could be the infrequent polishings, which
actually remove matter. On the other hand, if Le Gran K is
losing weight, it means that the force due to gravity is
lessening. This would make for a very grave situation,
indeed, for it would indicate either that the universal
constant of gravitation is not, in fact, a constant or that
the mass of the Earth is slowly decreasing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Neither of these alternatives is palatable, for they both
violate fundamental concepts of physics. The second
alternative, that the mass of the Earth is decreasing, could
possibly be attributed to the detonation of nuclear bombs,
each of which destroys a small amount of matter.
   In view of the gravity of this matter I believe we must
mass our forces to lessen the burden of the weight of the
problem.
   Irving R. Tannenbaum
   Professor of Chemistry
   West Los Angeles College
   Culver City, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Japan Taps Unlikely Oil Source -- Itself
   ---
   Hard-Luck Domestic Drillers
   Keep Fingers Crossed
   ----
   By Marcus W. Brauchli
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN J.JPE J.TEI
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   HIGASHI-KUBIKI, Japan -- "It's the best rig money can
buy," says engineer Ken Fujii about the towering, rumbling
oil-drilling rig he operates in the lush rice paddies of this
once-quiet mountain hamlet. "If there is oil, we'll find it."
   Oil? In a country that takes a perverse pride in calling
itself a vulnerable island with few natural resouces? Sure,
says Kazuhiko Itano, an assistant director of Japan National
Oil Corp., or JNOC. "We are an oil-producing country."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Not much of one, perhaps, but hope springs eternal --
though oil doesn't -- in the Japanese oil patch. So far, Mr.
Fujii, Japan's chief oil driller, and his geologists at
Higashi-Kubiki haven't displayed any Beverly Hillbilly luck.
Three of every four wells drilled in Japan are dry. Indeed,
Japan's first producing oil field wasn't found until 1891,
after 18 years of dry holes.
   But these days Japan's oil men feel themselves under more
pressure to perform. The prospect of war in the Persian Gulf
bodes ill for the economic superpower's health. Japan is the
world's second-largest oil consumer, after the U.S.,
dependent on oil for two-thirds of its energy. Acutely aware
of that dependence, Japan's oil companies are boring away
across Japan with missionary zeal.
   In the commuter-infested neighborhood of Chiba in suburban
Tokyo, small wells squeak the night away. In the rice-farming
hamlets of Niigata and Akita prefectures, where the winter
snows fall so heavily that some old wooden houses have
second-story doors, rusted skeletons of oil rigs are common.
A dozen miles off the coast of Niigata City, the flame of an
offshore oil platform burns day and night.
   The Japanese quest mixes patriotism and persistence. "We
are trying to make Japan more self-sufficient in energy,"
says an executive at a state-controlled oil company. "But it
may take time."
   Indeed. Japan imports 99% of its oil. Its purchases
account for one of every 10 barrels sold internationally. Few
Japanese know that their country produces even 1% of its oil.
   "Most local people aren't even aware what we're doing,"
says Mitsunobu Sugiyama, an administrator at Japan Petroleum
Exploration Co., the JNOC subsidiary operating the well in
Higashi-Kubiki.
   But, then, there's little reason they should be. The
Japanese oil men don't draw much attention to themselves.
This is no Cadillac-and-10-gallon-hat crowd. The favorite
hangout near Japan Petroleum's regional headquarters in
Niigata is a noodle shop where oil men shed their blue suit
jackets, loosen their ties, doff their shoes and slurp
seaweed noodles.
   Here at Higashi-Kubiki, the only roughneck is a giant
machinery trailer with the English words "Automatic
roughneck" stenciled on the side. Most everything is
automated, so the site requires only eight men a shift -- and
an aproned lady to serve steaming green tea or iced barley
tea.
   The strike-it-rich atmosphere of the Texas oil patch isn't
much in evidence here. Toshiki Takahashi, a 24-year-old
geologist at the Higashi-Kubiki rig, says: "The job is worth
doing because we make efforts to find oil for Japan even
though we don't know if it exists."
   Actually, there is considerable evidence that it doesn't.
Of the 1.33 billion barrels of oil Japan consumed in the
fiscal year ended March 31, domestic wells produced only 4.12
million barrels, or about 0.3%. The country's estimated
reserves are 52 million barrels; by contrast, Saudi Arabia
has 255 billion barrels.
   Still, nearly everybody in the Japanese oil industry seems
to know that Norway had no onshore oil to speak of before it
discovered vast offshore reserves in the early 1970s. Many
think they may replicate Norway's good fortune one day.
   "Of course there is always the possibility, a high
possibility, that we will find a large reserve because we
have this vast sea," says Takazo Ichimura, deputy manager of
Japan Petroleum's Niigata division. There's an even greater
chance, he adds, in the offshore shelf under seas that Japan
doesn't control at the moment but claims, such as those
around the Soviet-held Kuril island chain north of Japan.
   Japan's hunger for oil has caused it trouble in the past.
In 1941, after Franklin D. Roosevelt tried to cut off
Imperial Japan from the oil fields of Indonesia, Tokyo
attacked Pearl Harbor and occupied Indonesia. When the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries choked the
world's oil supply in 1973, Japan's economy ground
temporarily to a halt and inflation soared. This time around,
fears of an oil shortage have crippled the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, and interest rates have begun to creep up.
   Such agonies -- along with legends about Japanese emperors
a millenium ago burning oil that seeped from the ground --
give oil an almost mythical importance in Japan. The
government takes domestic exploration so seriously that
computers monitoring Mr. Fujii's 18,000-foot-deep well 200
miles from Tokyo beam signals to screens at Japan Petroleum's
headquarters, where officials of the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry can watch the progress.
   Although only a few companies explore and pump oil or gas
in Japan, two of them, Japan Petroleum and Teikoku Oil Co.,
were started with government money. All get big subsidies, as
much as 80%, to explore for oil in Japan.
   Despite the easy money, finding young Japanese to work in
the business isn't easy. Mr. Takahashi, the geologist at the
Higashi-Kubiki rig, says he was the only one of 40 geology
students at his university to enter the oil business.
Salaries are poor, it's a low-visibility industry and work
conditions in the field are poor compared with the office
environment at other big companies, he says.
   The few who choose oil do so because their country needs
them. "Japan needs a stable supply of oil from Japan," says
Mr. Itano of JNOC. Trying to convince the world that it will
find a real source isn't easy, though.
   "I used to start my speeches in Washington by telling U.S.
oil people that Japan is an oil producer," he says. "It made
them laugh."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0118
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0118.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Unlisted Shares Fall With Big Board;
   Sierra Tucson Dives on Earnings News
   ----
   By Craig S. Smith
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yet another new member of the Nasdaq club got hammered as
investors shun OTC stocks that deliver earnings
disappointments.
   Sierra Tucson, an operator of treatment centers for drug
abusers and people with mental disorders, lost 4 3/4 to 7 1/2
after lowering its sights on this year's earnings. The
company went public less than a year ago for $12 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While Sierra Tucson was the worst hit OTC stock yesterday,
it joins a growing list of stocks with short track records
that have been dealt devasting blows by nervous investors in
recent weeks.
   Digital Sound, Pharmacy Management Services, and In-Store
Advertising are among those stocks that are trading well
below their initial public offering prices set earlier this
year.
   Most of those companies have not lived up to the
expectations set during their offerings, and have paid dearly
as a result. Traders say there is little tolerance for
uncertainty in a market where even the best and the brightest
have lost their shine.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index fell 3.10 points, or 0.81%, to
378.68. The New York Stock Exchange Composite Index took a
bigger hit, dropping 1.4%.
   Tony Cecin, director of equity trading at Piper Jaffray &amp;
Hopwood, says Nasdaq dealer stock inventories are the lowest
that he has seen them in 10 years. That means OTC market
makers aren't willing to hold stock for long, and any shares
for sale will drive the stock price lower until a buyer is
found.
   OTC advancers trailed decliners, 796 to 1,015, while
volume fell to 106.3 million shares from 118.1 million shares
Wednesday.
   Piper Jaffray's Mr. Cecin says he won't feel comfortable
buying stocks until the market is much lower.
   He says that even if the Middle East crisis were settled
today and the Dow industrials rallied 150 points, there would
still be plenty of investors ready to sell their shares --
leading to another slide.
   "I would feel more comfortable about stepping in at 2,200
{on the Dow Jones Industrial Average} than at 2,450," he
says. The DJIA closed at 2,593.32, down 39.11 points
yesterday.
   Sierra Tucson's stock has lost more than half of its value
since Tuesday. Wednesday afternoon, Oppenheimer &amp; Co. analyst
Carl Sherman told his sales force and trading desk that
Sierra Tucson wouldn't meet his 1990 earnings projections,
traders of the stock say.
   Mr. Sherman lowered his 1990 projection to 73 cents a
share from an earlier range of 90 cents to 95 cents a share.
   Word of Mr. Sherman's views spread quickly, sparking a
sell-off that sent Sierra Tucson's stock plunging 4 points to
12 1/4 before the trading was halted late Wednesday.
   Later that day, Sierra Tucson announced that its new
German operations aren't going to break out of the red as
early as the company had hoped. Sierra opened a treatment
center in Germany late in 1989, but has yet to turn a profit
there.
   As a result, the company said profit for the third quarter
will fall below the 20 cents a share earned in the period
last year.
   "It's a timing issue," said Sierra Tucson's Chief
Financial Officer John Schmitz. "We made a mistake in terms
of projecting when we will break even" in Germany.
   Mr. Schmitz says the company now expects the German
operations to pass the break-even point early next year -- by
February at the latest. But Mr. Schmitz is dismayed by the
violent market reaction to the company's news.
   "The reaction is a little more negative than it needs to
be," he says of the decline in the company's stock. Even at
73 cents a share, Sierra Tucson's 1990 profit will have grown
15% year-over-year.
   Intel led the most-active list, falling 1 7/8 to 33 1/8 on
volume of more than two million shares. At least part of that
move was because of jitters over the impact of a patent
granted to a California-based inventor that could cover many
of the chips made by the semiconductor industry. This
newspaper reported that if the patent survives challenges,
chip-makers like Intel might have to fork over millions in
royalties.
   MCI Communications rose 7/8 to 32 5/8. In a meeting
Wednesday, the company assured Wall Street analysts that
their 1991 earnings estimates of $3.20 to $3.45 a share were
reasonable. That would translate into revenue growth of as
much as 20% for 1991, an MCI spokesman told Dow Jones
Professional Investor Report.
   Sunrise Medical added 1/2 to 14 1/4 after reporting that
it earned 40 cents a share on a fully diluted basis in its
fourth quarter ended in June, up from 32 cents a share in the
quarter last year.
   Envirosafe Services tumbled 4 7/8, or about 32%, to 10
3/8. The Ohio Hazardous Waste Facility Board denied an
application by one of the company's principal units to
construct an additional waste-disposal site in Ohio.
</TEXT>
