<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Safety Group
   Cites Fatalities
   Linked to Work
   ----
   By Ron Winslow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Occupational diseases kill more than 70,000 U.S. workers
yearly, says a workplace safety group that calls the issue
the nation's "most neglected public health problem."
   The National Safe Workplace Institute, an advocacy group
with headquarters in Chicago, based its estimate on an
analysis of 1987 data. The institute's report is among the
few efforts made to determine the prevalence of
workplace-related illnesses nationwide.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The report claims that occupational disease is a
substantial problem that isn't sufficiently recognized," says
Howard Frumkin, director of environmental and occupational
health at Emory University, Atlanta, and an adviser to the
institute.
   The report also says the nation's regulatory apparatus for
occupational health is in disarray. Standards for exposure to
many dangerous materials are much more lax for the workplace
than for the community at large, the report notes. It also
says funding for the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration and the National Institute for Occupational
Safety and Health, as a percentage of the federal budget,
fell sharply through the 1980s.
   Diane Porter, assistant director of NIOSH, said the study
"covers an important area that we need to look at." She also
noted that while the National Centers for Disease Control
tracks such infectious diseases as AIDS and measles on a
weekly basis, no national reporting system tracks
occupational disease. A spokesman for OSHA said agency
officials hadn't yet evaluated the study.
   The institute said it based its fatality report on data
from the National Center for Health Statistics and on
established methods to estimate the proportion of deaths from
major diseases that could be attributed to workplace
exposures. For instance, it estimated that 5% to 10% of the
nation's 483,000 cancer deaths in 1987 were related to
previous occupational exposures to dangerous substances,
while 1% to 3% of 964,000 cardiovascular disease deaths and
2% to 4% of 164,000 pulmonary disease fatalities were caused
by such exposures. The estimate of total occupational disease
deaths ranged from 47,377 to 95,479.
   Such numbers are inherently imprecise, the institute
acknowledged, because the onset of many occupational diseases
occurs many years after the initial exposure and doctors
often can't distinguish between illnesses that begin in the
workplace and those that develop from other causes.
   The institute said a broad effort by industry, medicine,
labor and government is necessary to develop more information
about the problem as well as effective programs to address
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0072
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0072.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Chemical Possibly Tied
   To EMS Outbreak Isolated
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Researchers at the Centers for Disease Control
said they isolated a chemical substance that may have
contaminated batches of L-tryptophan, a nutritional
supplement that triggered an outbreak of a rare blood
disorder earlier this year.
   About 1,500 cases of the illness, known as
eosinophilia-myalgia syndrome or EMS, have been linked to
consumption of L-tryptophan during the past 12 months,
according to the CDC. The disease involves abnormally high
levels of white blood cells, causing serious muscle pain,
neurological damage and, in some cases, death -- 27 people
have died from the disorder.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   CDC investigators said they are trying to determine
whether the isolated substance is the cause of the disease or
simply a "marker" of the actual cause. Scientists said they
don't know how the contaminant may have gotten into
L-tryptophan.
   Last December, the Food and Drug Administration banned
imports of L-tryptophan. Before that, virtually all
L-tryptophan sold in U.S. products were made by about six
Japanese companies.
   Earlier this month, Showa Denko K.K., Japan's
third-largest chemical producer, said 89 suits seeking a
total of $810 million in damages have been filed against the
company in the U.S. by victims of EMS. Until sales were
stopped, Showa exported about 70 tons of L-tryptophan a year
to the U.S.
   A report published in mid-August in the New England
Journal of Medicine said the outbreak of the disease probably
stemmed from a change in Showa's manufacturing process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0071
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0071.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hedged Securities
   To File Chapter 11
   Petition, Lawyer Says
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   WY UTH
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. -- Hedged Securities Associates Inc. and
its founder, James D. Donahue, plan to file today for
protection under the federal Bankruptcy Code, according to
Robert Dill, an attorney who represents Mr. Donahue and the
firm.
   Mr. Dill said Hedged Securities, a limited partnership,
plans to file under Chapter 11, which gives businesses
protection from creditors while formulating a reorganization
plan. Mr. Donahue plans to file under Chapter 13, which gives
similar protection to individuals, Mr. Dill said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The planned filings mark the latest chapters in an
investment scandal that began unfolding last week when Mr.
Donahue told a meeting of 500 investors that he had lost more
than $100 million of their money through stock-option
trading. Mr. Donahue's message was made via videotape.
   Weyerhaeuser Co., based in Tacoma, Wash., filed a lawsuit
yesterday in U.S. District Court in Denver accusing Mr.
Donahue of fraud, breach of contract and violation of certain
federal retirement securities laws. Weyerhaeuser said its
pension fund lost an estimated $35 million by investing in
Hedged Securities.
   In a lawsuit filed last week in a state district court
here, Paradigm Partners Inc. of Chicago said a pension fund
it controls lost more than $15 million through its Hedged
Securities investments. In a similar suit, Houston-based
Union Texas Petroleum Holding Inc. said its pension fund lost
about $8 million.
   On Wednesday, attorneys for Paradigm and Union Texas asked
a state judge to appoint a receiver to take over the troubled
firm. Hedged Securities staved off that action by agreeing
not to oppose the appointment of a receiver if it fails to
file for bankruptcy by early this afternoon.
   Mr. Dill said the "sheer volume of names and contracts"
prevented Hedged Securities from making a bankruptcy filing
earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
