<HL>
   Business Brief -- Atalanta/Sosnoff Capital Corp.:
   Board Authorizes Buy-Back
   Of About 200,000 Shares
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ATL
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Atalanta/Sosnoff Capital Corp. said its board has
authorized a buy-back of as many as 200,000 shares of its
common stock in open-market transactions.
   Atalanta, New York, said the timing of the purchases will
depend on market conditions. The asset management firm, once
a highflier on Wall Street, currently has about 10 million
shares outstanding. A spokesman said the board saw this as a
good time to get the stock at a price below book value.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company's earnings and assets have all fallen during
the first six months of 1990. Net income dropped 38% to $1.8
million, or 21 cents a share, for the first half from against
$2.9 million, or 35 cents a share, a year earlier. Assets
under Atalanta/Sosnoff's management have also dipped to $1.2
billion at June 30, compared with $1.7 billion last year.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday,
Atalanta/Sosnoff closed at $2.875, up 37.5 cents a share.
</TEXT>
