<HL>
   International Brief -- Esselte AB:
   Swedish Firm's Pretax Profit
   Plunged 70% in First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   S.ESL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   After reporting a 70% plunge in first-half pretax profit,
Sweden's Esselte AB slashed its full-year profit forecast by
50% and said it will intensify a world-wide cost-reduction
drive including hefty job cuts at all major divisions.
   Esselte, the world's biggest office-supplies group, blamed
the need for retrenchment on a surprisingly rapid downturn in
key markets that accelerated during the second quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company's chief executive officer, Hans Larsson,
declined to estimate how many jobs would be lost. He said
details would be disclosed within a month.
   Esselte said first-half profit before tax plunged to 97
million Swedish kronor ($16.9 million) from 327 million
kronor a year earlier. Operating profit skidded 26% to 445
million kronor from 603 million kronor the previous year,
with divisions for office products and information systems
reporting the steepest declines.
   Esselte's financial costs during the period ballooned 49%
to 295 million kronor -- mainly the result of heavy borrowing
to finance several acquisitions last year. First-half sales
increased 7.7% to 8.56 billion kronor from 7.95 billion
kronor a year earlier, the company said.
</TEXT>
