<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canon Earnings
   Rose 55% in Half
   On Brisk Demand
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4C
</SO>
<CO>
   CANNY
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Canon Inc., a major Japanese maker of cameras and
business machines, said that its consolidated pretax earnings
in the first half of the year surged 55% to 64.17 billion yen
($446.8 million) from 41.29 billion yen a year earlier,
because of brisk demand.
   Net income in the six months ended June 30 jumped 55% to
25.61 billion yen, or 32.55 yen a share, from 16.54 billion
yen, or 22.17 yen a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales amounted to 832.82 billion yen, showing a 33% gain
from 627.7 billion yen.
   Encouraged by the brisk results, Canon said it has revised
its 1990 earnings projections upward. It now sees pretax
earnings at about 140 billon yen, sharply higher than an
initial estimate of 105 billion yen made in February. Net is
estimated at 55 billion yen, up from an original 43 billion
yen projection. Canon expects 1990 sales to total some 1.7
trillion yen, rising from 1.5 trillion yen.
   Canon officials said the company has decided to revise the
projections in light of stronger-than-expected demand.
   In the first half, they said, demand was brisk for such
products as copiers, laser beam printers and other computer
peripherals, as well as facsimile machines.
   Sales in the business machines division climbed 31% to
665.58 billion yen, accounting for as much as 80% of the
company's entire business.
   Camera sales came to 114.43 billion yen, up 52% from a
year earlier. Single-lens reflex cameras, as well as 8mm
video equipment, helped sustain sales, Canon officials said.
   Sales of optical machines and other related products rose
18% to 52.81 billion yen. Equipment for the production of
semiconductors was among the products that officials said
contributed to the healthy gain.
   During the six months, Canon did 71% of its business
overseas, with sales totaling 591.38 billion yen. They
represented a 38% year-to-year surge.
   Domestic sales climbed 21% to 241.45 billion yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900831-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900831-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Notable &amp; Quotable
</HL>
<DATE>
08/31/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<LP>
   From a July 13 bulletin by the AFL-CIO's American
Institute for Free Labor Development:
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Militant eagerness to strike is a notably new posture for
Sandinista labor officials. In 1984, the ATC's Garcia
{Sandinista Association of Rural Workers chief Edgardo
Garcia} defended the Sandinista government's decision to
outlaw strikes on the grounds that "to strike would be to
deliver ourselves to the counter-revolution and U.S.
aggression. . . . Instead of strikes, we have decided that
mutual dialogue is the way to resolve disputes." In 1985,
Jimenez {Lucio Jimenez, chief of the Sandinista Workers
Central, or CST} explained the CST position this way: "We do
not want strikes. What we want is, for example, orders for
machetes not to fall behind. Why not? Because if we do not
have machetes we cannot carry out the sugar harvest." . . .
   Since their inception, the Sandinista labor organizations
assumed what the leftwing Guardian newspaper called "the role
of allies of management in increasing output." In January
1987, for example, Jimenez criticized sugar workers who "did
not respond with all their capacity to the demands of the
revolution for an increase in their productive output." In
its May Day slogans of 1988, the CST exhorted its members to
"fight inflation with more production, not strikes," and
"fight against inefficiency in the workplace." . . .
   Are the Sandinista unions now converting themselves into
organizations that represent the interests of workers? To the
members of independent unions like CUS {Confederation of
Trade Union Unity}, the answer is a resounding "no." "The
underlying issue is power, pure and simple," stated Jose
Espinoza of CUS. "The Sandinista unions are still arms of the
Sandinista front, regardless of what demands they put
forward," he said. "Their willingness to drag this country
down to achieve their `government from below' has further
alienated the workers."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
